refentry:

  SNMP::get
  Fetch an SNMP object



  &reftitle.description;


   public mixedSNMP::get
   arraystringobjectId
   boolpreserveKeys&false;


   Fetch an SNMP object specified in
   objectId using GET query.




  &reftitle.parameters;

  If objectId is a string, then SNMP::get
  will return SNMP object as string. If
  objectId is an array, all requested SNMP
  objects will be returned as associative array of the SNMP object ids and their
  values.



   objectId


     The SNMP object (OID) or objects




   preserveKeys


     When objectId is an array and
     preserveKeys set to &true; keys in results
     will be taken exactly as in objectId,
     otherwise SNMP::oid_output_format property is used to determinate
     the form of keys.







  &reftitle.returnvalues;

   Returns SNMP objects requested as string or array
   depending on objectId type or &false; on error.



 &snmp.methods.exceptions_enable.refsect;


  &reftitle.examples;

   Single SNMP object

     Single SNMP object may be requested in two ways: as
     string resulting string return value or as single-element array with
     associative array as output.



<?php
  $session = new SNMP(SNMP::VERSION_1, "127.0.0.1", "public");
  $sysdescr = $session->get("sysDescr.0");
  echo "$sysdescr\n";
  $sysdescr = $session->get(array("sysDescr.0"));
  print_r($sysdescr);
?>


   &example.outputs.similar;


STRING: Test server
Array
(
    [SNMPv2-MIB::sysDescr.0] => STRING: Test server
)




   Multiple SNMP objects


  $session = new SNMP(SNMP::VERSION_1, "127.0.0.1", "public");
  $results = $session->get(array("sysDescr.0", "sysName.0"));
  print_r($results);
  $session->close();


   &example.outputs.similar;


Array
(
    [SNMPv2-MIB::sysDescr.0] => STRING: Test server
    [SNMPv2-MIB::sysName.0] => STRING: myhost.nodomain
)






  &reftitle.seealso;

   SNMP::getErrno
   SNMP::getError
